Analysis of the Chipotle Dataset

The dataset can be found here: https://github.com/TheUpshot/chipotle/blob/master/orders.tsv

Context information for which purposes the dataset was collected is given in this article: https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2015/02/17/upshot/what-do-people-actually-order-at-chipotle.html

Short Description: The dataset was originally collected around 2015 to get insights into typcial orders at the fast-food chain "Chipotle". The data does not directly come from Chipotle restaurants, but from the US food delivery service Grubhub. This is important to know, because this fact may influence orders (e.g. less softdrinks).

The dataset consists of 1834 orders, that are described by the columns order_id, quantity, item_name, choice_description and item_price. The same order_id appears multiple times to indicate that an order consists of multiple items.

The analysis consists of four main tasks:

  • Data Cleaning and Extension
  • Descriptive Statistics
  • Correlations between attributes
  • Clustering

#correct lists of the choice_description

#then replace all the brackets and insert quotes so the strings are parsed correctly
df['choice_description'] = df.choice_description.apply(
    lambda x: literal_eval(('\'' + x.replace('[','').replace(']','').replace(',','\',\'') + '\'').replace(' ','').replace('-','').replace('Braised','').strip())
)

Now lets clean the string columns (item_name, choice_description) from whitespaces and correct the dashes and spaces variants in the Tomatillo Salsa. Somtimes there is a dash and sometimes there is a space. Just in case this becomes a problem we replace it by a space.

Other thing we found out was that the option of "braised" is not really an option and like this every time. So we remove the "braised".

Also we could find out that there is categories of items:

  • BurritoBowl
  • Burrito
  • Salad
  • SaladBowl
  • Crispy Taco
  • Soft Taco
  • Chips
  • Drinks

We will add a item category for them.

Further we will add a meat category filled with the kind of meat or veggie or NaN if there is no option for it.

In [40]:
#returns the item class as string
def item_class(n):
    if 'Bowl' in n:
        if 'Salad' in n:
            return 'SaladBowl'
        elif 'Chicken' in n:
            return 'ChickenBowl'
        return 'BurritoBowl'
    if 'Crispy' in n:
        return 'CrispyTaco'
    if 'Taco' in n:
        return 'SoftTaco'
    if 'Burrito' in n:
        return 'Burrito'
    if 'Salad' in n:
        return 'Salad'
    if 'Chips' in n:
        return 'Chips'
    return 'Drink'

#returns the meat option if there is one
def meat_option(n):
    if 'Steak' in n:
        return 'Steak'
    if 'Chicken' in n:
        return 'Chicken'
    if 'Carnitas' in n:
        return 'Carnitas'
    if 'Barbacoa' in n:
        return 'Barbacoa'
    if 'Veggie' in n:
        return 'Veggie'
    return 'No meat'

Descriptive Statistics

Analysis of the dataset using descriptive statistics on the level of individual attributes is a little sparse on our dataset, as we do not have too many proper numerical data columns.

So, the individual attributes used will be:

  • item_price_clean
  • quantity
  • a normalized item_price_clean by dividing it by the quantity
  • the aggregate order_total and quantity for the entire order

First of all, we start by invesitgating the item_price_clean and quantity, and afterwards we shall look an the aggregate values.

We are going to look at nice distribution plots for all these values, putting them in 20 bins, and afterwards calculating the mean, median, and standard deviation for all investigated attributes.

In [48]:

Investigating the results from these attributes tells us quite a bit about our data:

  • Firstly, most people order only one copy of the exact same item
  • The most common price of singular items is in between 8 and 9 dollars
  • But also very cheap singular items, as well as singular items above 11 dollars are often purchased. This is probably due to large meals (or combo deals) as well as very cheap sides like chips being quite popular.

  • Which choices are paired together
  • What kind of meat/souce is mostly chosen for a specific item menu

def printMinMaxCorrs(df,n):  
    maxDf = pd.DataFrame()
    minDf = pd.DataFrame()
    for col in df:
       maxDf[col] =  sorted(df[col], reverse = True)[:2]
       minDf[col] =  sorted(df[col])[:1]
    maxDf = maxDf.T.sort_values(by = 1, ascending = False)[1].head(n)
    minDf = minDf.T.sort_values(by = 0, ascending = True)[0].head(n)
    for index in maxDf.index:
        print(index + " + " + df[index].loc[df[index] >= maxDf[index]].sort_values(ascending = True).index[0] + " (" + str(maxDf[index]) + ")" )
    print("===========================")
    for index in minDf.index:
        print(index + " + " + df[index].loc[df[index] <= minDf[index]].sort_values(ascending = False).index[0] + " (" + str(minDf[index]) + ")" )
    return

printMinMaxCorrs(dfChoices_corr,8)

Clustering

Clustering is part of unsupervised learning and its goal is to find groups of similar objects and possibly discover interesting patterns. Since clustering is mostly based on visual insights, we need to downproject our data into lower dimensional space (2D).

Opposed to supervised learning in clustering it is often not clear beforehand, what do we want to discover. Mostly we cluster the data, analyze if there are interesting patterns and only then try to interpret the results. Since this also holds for our dataset and we don't even know from the beginning, which parts of the dataset we want to use for clustering and visual inspection our goal is to provide a generic and flexible overview that provides the following configuration possibilities:

  • Select the columns that should be used for clustering. In particular the user should be able to select between the columns quantity, item_price_clean, order_total and the side-dish choices.
  • Select two different types of clustering algorithms: here we choose KMEANS and DBSCAN.
  • Choose most important parameters of the clustering algorithms.
  • Select particular clusters that seem to be interesting.
  • Analyse the distribution of the selected samples in relation to the generated categorical columns item_class and meat_option. In addition to that we want to see the average price of the items that are selected.

This structure allows also to investigate a relationship that seems interesting and promising:

  • If we downproject and cluster the side-dishes, can we find clusters corresponding to the self-generated categorical attributes item_class and meat_option? Can we find clusters that correspond to the price?

In [57]:
# we do not want to pass everything via parameters, so we define a context
current_context = {}

def reset_context():
    global current_context 
    current_context = {
        'data': {'choices': choice_list, 'item_price': item_price, 'order_total': order_total, 'quantity': quantity},
        'pca_data': None,  # must be of shape (4622, 2) -> 2 dimensions
        'selected_data_rows': np.full(shape=(len(choice_list),), fill_value=False), # indices of selected datapoints
        'bar_target': {'item_class': df['item_class'], 'meat_option': df['meat_option']},
        'price_stats': {'item_price_clean': df['item_price_clean']}, # used to calculate average price
        'clusters':{}, # maps class labels to corresponding indices
        'display_data': df[['quantity', 'choice_description', 'item_price']]
    }

def set_pca_data(data):
    global current_context 
    current_context['pca_data'] = data

def set_cluster(label, indices):
    global current_context 
    current_context['clusters'][label] = indices
    
reset_context()

To be able to visually inspect high-dimensional data we need to downproject to 2D space. One possibility to do this is by applying Principal Component Analysis (PCA). Reducing dimensions comes with loss of information, of course, but PCA tries to preserve as much information as possible. To quantify this loss of information, we look at an important measure: the explained variance ratio. This tells us how much of the original information (variance) is preserved by the two principal components we use for plotting.

In [58]:
# downprojection via pca
from sklearn import decomposition

def run_pca(data):
    pca = decomposition.PCA(n_components=2, random_state=99)
    transformed_data = pca.fit(data).transform(data)
    print("Explained variance by PC 1 and PC 2: ", pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
    return transformed_data

The first clustering algorithm is K-means. With K-means the number of clusters must be specified beforehand. The algorithm then tries minimize the within-cluster-sum-of-squares, also called inerta, in an expectation-maximization process. The final intertia will be printed to be able to quantify the performance of the algorithm.

In [59]:
# first cluster algorithm: KMEANS
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

# one parameter: the number of clusters
def run_kmeans(n_clusters):
    data = current_context['pca_data']
    instance = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, random_state = 99)
    clusters_assignment = instance.fit_predict(data)
    unique_labels = np.unique(clusters_assignment)
    # store the cluster membership mask in context variable
    for label in unique_labels:
        set_cluster(str(label) + ". cluster", clusters_assignment == label)
    plt.scatter(data[:, 0], data[:, 1], s=20, c=[colors[label] for label in clusters_assignment])
    patches = [mpatches.Patch(color=colors[label], label=str(label) + ". cluster") for label in unique_labels]
    # place legend to the right side of the plot
    plt.legend(handles=patches, bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
    plt.title('KMEANS: number of clusters: %d' % n_clusters)
    plt.show()
    print("K-Means within-cluster-sum-of-squares: %.2f\n" % instance.inertia_)
    # is defined in one of the next cells - necessary for interactively choosing the clusters
    update_cluster_list(unique_labels)

As a second cluster algorithm we choose DBSCAN, since this algorithm works very different from K-means and usually also leads to very different clusters. DBSCAN is density-based, which means it clusters areas with high density. Instead of specifying a fixed number of cluster beforehand, DBSCAN takes the arguments eps (a distance) and min_samples (integer number). Then it tries to find core samples that have at least min_samples within a radius of eps. Multiple core samples within a radius of eps form a cluster. A sample without a core point in its eps-radius is an outlier and labelled as -1. The parameter min_samples primarily controls how tolerant the algorithm is to noise, while eps must be chosen appropriately according to the distances in a particular dataset.

In [60]:
# second cluster algorithm: DBSCAN
from sklearn.cluster import DBSCAN

# adapted from: 
# https://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/cluster/plot_dbscan.html#sphx-glr-auto-examples-cluster-plot-dbscan-py
# two parameters:
# eps ... maximum distance for two samples to be considered as neighbors
# min_samples ... amount of neighbouring samples needed for a sample to considered a core point 
def run_dbscan(eps, min_samples):
    data = current_context['pca_data']
    db = DBSCAN(eps=eps, min_samples=min_samples).fit(data)
    labels = db.labels_
    unique_labels = set(labels)
    n_clusters_ = len(unique_labels) - (1 if -1 in labels else 0)
    n_noise_ = list(labels).count(-1) # samples with label -1 are considered noise points
    core_samples_mask = np.zeros_like(labels, dtype=bool)
    core_samples_mask[db.core_sample_indices_] = True # mask for core points
    marker = 'o'
    for i, (k, col) in enumerate(zip(unique_labels, colors)):
        if k == -1:
            # Black used for noise.
            col = [0, 0, 0, 1]

        class_member_mask = (labels == k)
        # store class member mask in current context variable
        set_cluster(str(k) + ". cluster", class_member_mask)
        
        # plot and define layout of core points and non-core points
        xy = data[class_member_mask & core_samples_mask]
        plt.plot(xy[:, 0], xy[:, 1], marker, markerfacecolor=tuple(col), markeredgecolor='k', markersize=6)

        xy = data[class_member_mask & ~core_samples_mask]
        plt.plot(xy[:, 0], xy[:, 1], marker, markerfacecolor=tuple(col), markeredgecolor='k', markersize=3)
    
    # this is a bit tricky, since we don't know the number of clusters beforehand
    # not a nice solution, but it does not makes sense to display a huge number of clusters
    if len(unique_labels) > len(colors):
        unique_labels = list(unique_labels)[:len(colors)]
    patches = [mpatches.Patch(color=colors[i], label=str(label) + ". cluster") for i, label in enumerate(unique_labels)]
    # place legend to the right side of the plot
    plt.legend(handles=patches, bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
    plt.title('DBCSAN: estimated number of clusters: %d' % n_clusters_)
    plt.show()
    print("Number of noise points detected: %d\n" % np.sum(labels == -1))
    # is defined in one of the next cells - necessary for interactively choosing the clusters
    update_cluster_list(unique_labels)

The two procedures in the following cell control interactive elements:

  • update_cluster_list(labels): allows to select the clusters that should be analyzed in detail and further allows to select the target attribute for the barplot
  • on_cluster_selection_change(cluster_selection, target_selection): uses all the selections to display the final barplot and the average item price within the selected samples
In [61]:
from ipywidgets import widgets, interact
from tabulate import tabulate

# after running clustering, we want to select clusters for detail analysis 
def update_cluster_list(labels):
    print("Select the clusters you want to analyse in detail (multi selection by holding Ctrl): ")
    # cluster selection widget
    multi_select = widgets.SelectMultiple(options=[str(label) + ". cluster" for label in labels], description="Selection")
    # selection of categorical attribute for histogram
    bar_target = widgets.RadioButtons(options=list(current_context['bar_target'].keys()),
                                       description="Barplot Target")
    interact(on_cluster_selection_change, cluster_selection=multi_select, target_selection=bar_target)
    
# present results of detailed cluster analysis
def on_cluster_selection_change(cluster_selection, target_selection):
    selected_clusters = cluster_selection
    all_clusters = current_context['clusters']
    data_selection = current_context['selected_data_rows']
    # collect samples of all selected clusters in a mask
    for cluster in selected_clusters:
         data_selection = np.logical_or(data_selection, all_clusters[cluster])
    
    nr_dp = np.sum(data_selection)
    print("Number of selected data points: ", nr_dp)
    if nr_dp > 0:
        current_context['bar_target'][target_selection][data_selection].value_counts().plot(kind='bar')
        print("Average price of items in cluster: %.2f" %
              current_context['price_stats']['item_price_clean'][data_selection].mean())

The init_app(data_selection, algo_selection) procedure finally runs the app by using all the procedures we defined so far. The process starts by questioning the user to choose the data and the algorithm that should be applied. Then it performs standardization followed by PCA and the actual clustering algorithm. The results and all interactive elements except the data and algorithm selection are created by the helper procedures defined above.

In [62]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

print("Start by selecting data (multi selection by holding Ctrl) and the algorithm:")
# starts the visualization and clustering application by letting the user choose the dataset columns and the algorithm
@interact(
    data_selection=widgets.SelectMultiple(options=list(current_context['data'].keys()), description="Data:"),
    algo_selection=widgets.RadioButtons(options=['KMEANS', 'DBSCAN'], description="Algo:")
)
def init_app(data_selection, algo_selection):
    reset_context() # reset context variable
    if len(data_selection) > 0:
        # first collect chosen columns in a data matrix
        data_mat = np.column_stack(tuple([current_context['data'][data_col] for data_col in data_selection])) \
                        .astype(np.float64)
        # we need at least 2 dimensions for pca
        if data_mat.shape[1] > 1:
            # only standardize if 'choices' columns not in selection -> 
            # this would give extremely low explained variance by pca
            if 'choices' not in data_selection:
                # scale data (makes finding appropriate parameters easier, important for DBSCAN)
                data_mat = StandardScaler().fit_transform(data_mat)
            # then perform pca
            set_pca_data(run_pca(data_mat)) # assign to current context
            # now perform clustering with the resulting 2D data
            if algo_selection == 'DBSCAN':
                interact(run_dbscan, eps=(0.01,1.0), min_samples=(1, 40))
            elif algo_selection == 'KMEANS':
                interact(run_kmeans, n_clusters=(1,len(colors)))
        else:
            print("Selected data must contain at least 2 feature columns")

Interpretation and Findings

It is very interesting to play around and see the differences between K-means and DBSCAN, also to get a notion of what density-based really means. While DBSCAN tends to detect one big cluster and lots of small island clusters mostly, K-means visually creates boundaries based on the position of the centroids.

Note: to keep the legend and diagram clear a maximum of 10 clusters (most prominant ones) is displayed

We will interpret two insteresting settings in detail in the following:

First Example: DBSCAN

  • Data: 'choices', Algo: 'DBSCAN', eps: 0.1, min_samples: 25: DBSCAN really needs very exact fine-tuning of parameters to get visually promising clusters with the selected data. Core points are visualized with a larger marker size than non-core points. Our two PCs explain around 45% of the total variance when reducing from 47 to 2 dimensions. Furthermore, in this setting 532/4622 points are noise points, which is quite a lot.
    • cluster: 0: leftmost cluster, contains 1246 data points containing over 1000 "Chips" items, points lie exactly on top of each other -> makes perfectly sense, since "Chips" do not come with side dishes (only zero vectors); additionally average item price in this cluster is with an average price of 3.27\$ very cheap (e.g. Chips are much cheaper than a Burrito)
    • cluster: 1: right of cluster 1, contains 538 smaples, nearly all of them are "Drinks", type of Drink is listed as side-dish, again very cheap: 2,60
    • cluster 4: 389 data points, more than half of them are "Burritos", therefore items in this cluster are expensive (9.52\$), side-dishes ordered with Burritos appear to have some similarities (salsa, rice, beans, ... are common)
    • cluster 5 and 6: 27 and 35 samples, are dominated by ChickenBowl, BurritoBowl, Burrito -> "meat" clusters (mostly chicken), most expensive ones with 12,43 and 12,86 Dollar on average
    • further details: the map seems to have an implicit sorting of the prices from left to right (without prices included in the clustering!), "Drinks" and "Chips" only appear in the clusters 0 and 1, other clusters are mostly dominated by "Burrito" (majority classes - 1150)

Second Example: KMEANS

The second example aims at finding clusters with uncommon distributions containing meat options. We will use K-means with n_cluster=6, since there are 6 meat option classes. Therefore it is important to know the distribution of all samples concerning meat_option:

  • Data: 'choices', 'item_price', 'quantity', Algo: 'KEMANS', n_clusers: 6: This time our two principal components (resulting from 49 downprojected dimensions) can explain more of the total variance than before (> 90%). All of the 4622 samples are displayed, since K-means does not filter out noise points.
    • clusters 1 and 5: contain together 1719 data points, which is a large portion of the total data set; interestingly this two clusters consist of only "no_meat" samples, if we look at the item_class distribution the clusters only contain "Drinks" and "Chips" (similar to what DBSCAN identified), cluster 1 has an average price of 1.89\$, which ist extremely cheap (cluster 5 with 4.49\$ also cheap)
    • cluster 3: "outlier" cluster, contains very expensive items (average: 31.38 Dollar, e.g. Steak is a bit more prominent than in other clusters),
    • cluster 4: even more dominated by Chicken and Steak than other classes, very expensive (19.05\$)

In this example the clusters become more expensive, the further on the right side of the plot they are located. This has the following (problematic) reason: The 'choice_description' column is one-hot encoded and therefore has 47 dimensions now. If we use those 47 columns, 'quantity' and 'item_price' and standardize the data, then the two principal components can only explain around 10\% of the total variance, which makes the clustering almost useless. Therefore we decided not to standardize the data if the 'choice' columns are included. This has the effect that the columns' magnitudes influence PCA. It is a logical consequence that the first PC (first axis) then picks up almost all of the signal of the 'item_price' column (highest magnitude).

How the clustering task is fulfilled:

1) Reducing the number of dimension using an appropriate technique (PCA)

2) Cluster algorithm and parameters can be interactively selected

3) One or more clusters can be selected

4) Selected data can be used in a second interactive visualization according to an overview+detail setup (barplot with radio buttons)

5) As a final step some findings have been interpreted
